    body: "Many Hispanic seniors who lived and worked in both Mexico and the United States face a confusing question when they retire. Did my time working in Mexico count toward US Social Security, and did my time in the United States count toward the Mexican Social Security system, called IMSS? The honest answer in 2026 is mixed. The United States and Mexico signed a totalization agreement in 2004 that would let workers combine credits from both countries to qualify for retirement benefits, but the agreement has not yet been put into force by Congress. As a result, you currently cannot combine US and Mexican credits the way you can with countries like Canada, Spain, Italy, or 30 other partner nations.\n\nHowever, this does not mean your work in either country was wasted. The United States Social Security system requires 40 credits, which is about 10 years of covered work in the United States, to qualify for retirement benefits. If you worked at least 10 years in the United States and paid Social Security taxes, you qualify for US benefits regardless of any work in Mexico. If you worked fewer than 10 years in the United States, you may still receive a small refund of taxes paid, but you do not qualify for a monthly benefit. Mexican IMSS pensions follow their own rules and are paid separately from US Social Security based only on time worked in Mexico.\n\nThis can feel unfair, especially for people who worked 8 or 9 years in the United States and 25 years in Mexico. The bipartisan Social Security Fairness Act passed in early 2025 removed the Windfall Elimination Provision, which used to reduce US benefits for people who also received foreign pensions. Now, if you qualify for US Social Security based on your US work alone, your full benefit amount is paid even if you also receive an IMSS pension from Mexico. This change is one of the biggest improvements for Hispanic retirees in decades.\n\nThis guide walks through how to check your US Social Security earnings record, how to contact the Mexican IMSS to claim a Mexican pension, what documents you need from both countries, how to apply for benefits in Spanish, and what changes in the totalization agreement might still come during the next few years. We also cover how to handle a denied claim, how to fix missing earnings, and how to make sure the bipartisan rules are applied to your benefit calculation.",
